00:34:08,046 --> 00:34:09,438
I believe that, Mitch, I do.

501
00:34:09,482 --> 00:34:11,658
But it's just...
Danny doesn't...

502
00:34:13,834 --> 00:34:16,358
Danny didn't have a temper.

503
00:34:16,402 --> 00:34:19,492
Hell, I always knew you two
as just high school
football heroes.

504
00:34:19,535 --> 00:34:21,842
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

505
00:34:21,885 --> 00:34:24,062
[GIRLS LAUGHING]

506
00:34:26,151 --> 00:34:27,935
[CROWD CHEERING]

507
00:34:38,554 --> 00:34:42,210
ANNOUNCER : [OVER PA]
...with 45 seconds left
on the clock,

508
00:34:42,254 --> 00:34:47,041
Tony Turner behind center
needs to convert here
to keep the drive alive.

509
00:34:47,085 --> 00:34:50,218
Turner calls an audible.
That's the snap.
Turner well into his left.

510
00:34:50,262 --> 00:34:53,178
Here comes the Blitz.
He's got a man open
down the line.

511
00:34:53,221 --> 00:34:56,006
Turner gets his brother Danny
at dead center!

512
00:34:56,050 --> 00:35:00,533
He's in the 15, the 10,
the five, touchdown!

513
00:35:00,576 --> 00:35:02,535
[CROWD CHEERING]

514
00:35:02,578 --> 00:35:05,712
The Cougars win the game.
The Cougars win the game.
Unbelievable!

515
00:35:05,755 --> 00:35:07,409
The Turner brothers
do it again.

516
00:35:07,453 --> 00:35:09,759
He's got them
to a final score of...

517
00:35:09,803 --> 00:35:13,415
[TRUMPET PLAYING NOTES]

518
00:35:13,459 --> 00:35:15,417
Danny? Hey, you okay?

519
00:35:15,461 --> 00:35:16,592
Yeah, hey...

520
00:35:16,636 --> 00:35:18,333
-YOUNG TONY:
Danny, let's go.
-Yeah.

521
00:35:18,377 --> 00:35:20,292
Am I gonna see you
at the party later?

522
00:35:20,335 --> 00:35:22,816
Sure. Um,
I want you to meet someone.

523
00:35:22,859 --> 00:35:26,036
Danny Turner,
this is Rachel McKenna.

524
00:35:26,080 --> 00:35:28,474
Danny scored
the winning touchdown today.

525
00:35:28,517 --> 00:35:30,171
Wow. Cool.

526
00:35:30,215 --> 00:35:31,651
-YOUNG TONY: Come on, man,
let's go!
-Nice to meet you, Danny.

527
00:35:31,694 --> 00:35:33,261
-Nice meeting you, too.
-[HORNS HONKING]

528
00:35:33,305 --> 00:35:35,307
-What did you say
your name was, Renee?
-No, it's Rach...

529
00:35:37,570 --> 00:35:39,572
It's Rachel.

530
00:35:39,615 --> 00:35:41,226
YOUNG TONY: We're late
for the kegger, man.

531
00:35:43,967 --> 00:35:45,969
TONY: When the scholarships
didn't come in,

532
00:35:46,013 --> 00:35:47,580
things eventually
kind of fell apart.

533
00:35:49,234 --> 00:35:51,671
That summer, Danny and I
picked up stock boy jobs

534
00:35:51,714 --> 00:35:53,803
at Tager's Lumber Yard
to make some extra money.

535
00:35:53,847 --> 00:35:54,978
But it was never enough.

536
00:35:55,022 --> 00:35:56,241
What do we got here?

537
00:35:56,284 --> 00:35:58,547
So we started
stealing inventory

538
00:35:58,591 --> 00:36:00,854
and fencing it to pick up
the extra bucks.

539
00:36:00,897 --> 00:36:05,206
I knew a guy in Baton Rouge
that would pay
25 bucks per saw.

540
00:36:05,250 --> 00:36:08,209
We could make $500.

541
00:36:08,253 --> 00:36:11,386
You have to understand,
we were making
minimum wage at the time.

542
00:36:11,430 --> 00:36:13,519
Things continued like that
for about a year.

543
00:36:13,562 --> 00:36:15,651
Then we got
a phone call from Bags.

544
00:36:15,695 --> 00:36:17,000
What's up, man?

545
00:36:17,044 --> 00:36:18,306
[POOL BALLS CLINKING]

546
00:36:18,350 --> 00:36:19,481
Nice.

547
00:36:20,874 --> 00:36:22,484
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

548
00:36:22,528 --> 00:36:24,051
YOUNG TONY: Yo, Bags. Over here.

549
00:36:25,531 --> 00:36:27,881
BAGS: Ah! There they are.

550
00:36:27,924 --> 00:36:30,753
-[LAUGHS] Yo, what's going on?
-What's up?

551
00:36:30,797 --> 00:36:32,799
Hey, Danny! Come here, bud.

552
00:36:32,842 --> 00:36:35,105
BAGS: How we doing, fellas?
YOUNG TONY: Good, good.

553
00:36:35,149 --> 00:36:37,586
BAGS: Good.
YOUNG TONY: What do you
got for us?

554
00:36:37,630 --> 00:36:39,458
I got something for you.

555
00:36:39,501 --> 00:36:41,460
You know that antique shop
over at Novelty?

556
00:36:41,503 --> 00:36:43,157
The one that sells
all that crap like

557
00:36:43,201 --> 00:36:45,725
old clocks and paintings
and tables and stuff?

558
00:36:45,768 --> 00:36:48,075
Well, I had to do
deliveries there every day,

559
00:36:48,118 --> 00:36:51,644
and I started getting friendly
with the big bald dude Jack
who hauls all the stuff around

560
00:36:51,687 --> 00:36:54,908
for the two old farts
that own the joint.
He said that they do a lot,

561
00:36:54,951 --> 00:36:59,086
[SNICKERING] and I mean,
a lot of business in cash,

562
00:36:59,129 --> 00:37:01,915
then they take it home
to their house in Lafayette.

563
00:37:03,569 --> 00:37:05,310
Cash!

564
00:37:05,353 --> 00:37:08,835
Say that's true,
how are we supposed to get
the cash out of the safe

565
00:37:08,878 --> 00:37:10,315
if we don't know
the combination.

566
00:37:11,490 --> 00:37:13,492
Jack knows the combination.

567
00:37:13,535 --> 00:37:16,277
Like, he won't do the break-in,

568
00:37:16,321 --> 00:37:19,062
but he'll give it to us
if we cut him in.

569
00:37:19,106 --> 00:37:21,978
Check this. He says that
they're planning
to go to Florida

570
00:37:22,022 --> 00:37:23,850
for a few months in January.

571
00:37:23,893 --> 00:37:25,765
If we give him
a 1,000 bucks upfront,

572
00:37:25,808 --> 00:37:27,984
he'll make us a copy
of the house key

573
00:37:28,028 --> 00:37:30,639
and give us the code
to the alarm system.

574
00:37:30,683 --> 00:37:32,337
Merry Christmas, boys.

575
00:37:32,380 --> 00:37:34,426
[ALL CHUCKLING]

576
00:37:34,469 --> 00:37:36,732
-[BANGING ON TABLE]
-Come on! Huh?

577
00:37:36,776 --> 00:37:39,387
Ho-ho-ho. [LAUGHS]

578
00:37:39,431 --> 00:37:42,477
TONY: Jack said
the safe was bolted
inside a cabinet upstairs.

579
00:37:44,131 --> 00:37:47,221
There was at least
$50,000 in it.

580
00:37:47,265 --> 00:37:49,745
Jack also said the homeowners,
Don and Linda Grant,

581
00:37:49,789 --> 00:37:53,314
they closed up shop
week after Christmas every year.

582
00:37:53,358 --> 00:37:56,099
Just put the lights on timers
and bolted out of town.

583
00:37:56,143 --> 00:38:00,582
So we hung out for a few days
just to make sure
the place was empty.

584
00:38:02,671 --> 00:38:06,153
We were so excited
because we had the keys.

585
00:38:09,243 --> 00:38:13,291
We weren't exactly pros
and we should've realized
at the time that the...

586
00:38:13,334 --> 00:38:14,683
YOUNG DANNY: Okay, go ahead.

587
00:38:14,727 --> 00:38:16,468
...the whole plan
rested on a stranger

588
00:38:16,511 --> 00:38:18,557
whose last name
we didn't even know.

589
00:38:18,600 --> 00:38:21,211
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
ON CAR STEREO]

590
00:38:29,176 --> 00:38:32,005
BAGS: Yo, Danny, turn it up.

591
00:38:33,702 --> 00:38:36,575
[MUSIC GETS LOUDER]

592
00:38:41,884 --> 00:38:44,800
[ELECTRIC GUITAR SOLO PLAYING]

593
00:38:47,237 --> 00:38:48,848
TONY: Kevin and Missy Grant

594
00:38:48,891 --> 00:38:52,025
were driving in
from Chicago that day.

595
00:38:52,068 --> 00:38:54,897
They were gonna stay
at the house for a few days

596
00:38:54,941 --> 00:38:56,334
before heading down to Florida

597
00:38:56,377 --> 00:38:57,857
to meet up
with Kevin's parents.

598
00:38:57,900 --> 00:38:59,206
[ALARM SYSTEM BEEPS]

599
00:38:59,946 --> 00:39:01,382
MISSY: Thank you.

600
00:39:01,426 --> 00:39:03,036
TONY: Kevin's parents
didn't know at the time

601
00:39:03,079 --> 00:39:04,646
that Missy
was three months pregnant.

602
00:39:06,300 --> 00:39:08,520
And we didn't know that
they were gonna to be there.

603
00:39:18,138 --> 00:39:19,226
[BAGS HUMMING]

604
00:39:26,451 --> 00:39:29,671
BAGS: Hey, how did you guys
get here before me?

605
00:39:32,370 --> 00:39:34,850
A tire iron?
The place is empty, Danny.

606
00:39:35,590 --> 00:39:37,549
What's the difference?

607
00:39:37,592 --> 00:39:40,508
TONY: We should have seen
that there was something wrong
with Danny,

608
00:39:40,552 --> 00:39:41,770
something in his head.

609
00:39:41,814 --> 00:39:43,642
I'll leave it in the gym bag
just in case.

610
00:39:43,685 --> 00:39:44,991
Forget it. Come on.

611
00:39:48,734 --> 00:39:51,824
YOUNG TONY: [WHISPERING]
What are you're doing?
Turn... Turn them off.

612
00:39:51,867 --> 00:39:53,391
Turn them off. Turn them off.

613
00:40:10,843 --> 00:40:12,453
[KEYPAD BEEPING]

614
00:40:12,497 --> 00:40:13,585
[ALARM BEEPS]

615
00:40:16,370 --> 00:40:19,329
-[UNLOCKING DOOR]
-[ALARM BEEPS]

616
00:40:24,596 --> 00:40:25,771
[ALARM BEEPS]

617
00:40:25,814 --> 00:40:28,077
TONY: That lamp bothered me.

618
00:40:28,121 --> 00:40:30,515
The lamp was off
when I knew that

619
00:40:30,558 --> 00:40:32,604
those lights were
supposed to be on a timer.

620
00:40:35,215 --> 00:40:36,346
[SHUSHING]

621
00:40:37,609 --> 00:40:38,653
Something's wrong.

622
00:40:38,697 --> 00:40:40,133
BAGS: [CHUCKLES] Chill, Tony.

623
00:40:40,176 --> 00:40:41,700
No one's here but us chickens.

624
00:40:42,483 --> 00:40:43,528
Let's go.

625
00:40:55,670 --> 00:40:57,542
-[FAINT LAUGHTER]
-[THUDDING]

626
00:40:57,585 --> 00:40:59,413
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

627
00:40:59,457 --> 00:41:00,719
Do you hear something?

628
00:41:02,982 --> 00:41:04,070
[MISSY MOANS]

629
00:41:09,510 --> 00:41:14,863
TONY: I remember how young
and frightened we all were.

630
00:41:14,907 --> 00:41:16,343
Danny in particular, his...

631
00:41:17,779 --> 00:41:20,652
his big old eyes
just talking out of his head.

632
00:41:22,567 --> 00:41:25,308
BAGS: Hey, give me a hand.

633
00:41:25,352 --> 00:41:27,485
BAGS: [WHISPERING]
Here, take this. Hold this up.

634
00:41:32,664 --> 00:41:35,057
[CHUCKLES] Oh, boy...

635
00:41:40,410 --> 00:41:43,544
[LAUGHING]

636
00:41:43,588 --> 00:41:45,677
BAGS: What did I tell you?
What did I tell you?

637
00:41:45,720 --> 00:41:47,766
There! Go on! Tony! Check!

638
00:41:47,809 --> 00:41:49,289
YOUNG TONY: All right.
Load it up.

639
00:41:52,205 --> 00:41:54,294
-[LOUD THUD]
-[BOTH GASP]

640
00:41:54,337 --> 00:41:56,339
[WHISPERING] There's
someone in the house.

641
00:41:56,383 --> 00:41:58,472
[BAGS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

642
00:42:10,049 --> 00:42:11,572
We have to call the cops.

643
00:42:19,145 --> 00:42:21,147
I left my phone downstairs.

644
00:42:21,190 --> 00:42:22,278
[THUDDING]

645
00:42:29,372 --> 00:42:30,765
Kevin, be careful.

646
00:42:37,163 --> 00:42:38,860
[BREATH TREMBLING]

647
00:42:52,265 --> 00:42:54,136
[BAGS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

648
00:42:55,790 --> 00:42:57,052
What the hell are you doing?

649
00:43:01,579 --> 00:43:04,016
Don't do anything stupid
and no one's gonna get hurt.

650
00:43:09,978 --> 00:43:10,979
Kevin?

651
00:43:12,285 --> 00:43:15,027
Missy, go downstairs,
call the cops. Now!

652
00:43:15,854 --> 00:43:17,551
[PANTING]

653
00:43:17,595 --> 00:43:18,944
YOUNG TONY: No, come back.

654
00:43:19,988 --> 00:43:22,295
[GRUNTS]

655
00:43:22,338 --> 00:43:24,514
TONY: So, Bill, when you say
that It's hard to believe
that Danny had a temper,

656
00:43:24,558 --> 00:43:26,647
I say that you did not know
Danny the way I did.

657
00:43:26,691 --> 00:43:27,953
[KEVIN GROANS]

658
00:43:31,521 --> 00:43:32,914
Bastard! [GRUNTING]

659
00:43:32,958 --> 00:43:37,136
-Don't... ever... hit... me.
-Get off, Danny!

660
00:43:38,093 --> 00:43:39,268
No, Danny!

661
00:43:39,312 --> 00:43:41,009
BAGS: Come on, chill out!
We gotta go!

662
00:43:42,054 --> 00:43:43,490
I'm outta here.

663
00:43:43,533 --> 00:43:44,534
Go!

664
00:43:47,450 --> 00:43:49,278
[PANTING] Where is it?
Where is it?

665
00:43:50,715 --> 00:43:51,672
[PHONE BEEPS]

666
00:43:52,760 --> 00:43:54,675
[MISSY SCREAMING]

667
00:43:54,719 --> 00:43:56,198
Call the cops and I'll kill you.

668
00:43:58,287 --> 00:43:59,811
Aah! [GRUNTS]

669
00:44:00,550 --> 00:44:02,378
[MISSY GROANS]

670
00:44:02,422 --> 00:44:04,554
[SOBBING]

671
00:44:07,732 --> 00:44:09,168
[MISSY GROANING IN PAIN]

672
00:44:21,746 --> 00:44:23,965
Bags took the cash. He bolted.
We went after him.

673
00:44:24,009 --> 00:44:26,751
He was tearing down
Highway 10 in Henderson and...

674
00:44:28,491 --> 00:44:29,667
[SIGHS]

675
00:44:31,451 --> 00:44:34,584
He collided with a tree
on the side of the road.

676
00:44:34,628 --> 00:44:36,543
And half of him
went through the windshield.

677
00:44:39,024 --> 00:44:41,461
Danny and I got back
to our house and the cops
were already there.

678
00:44:41,504 --> 00:44:43,158
They're waiting for us
because it turns out

679
00:44:43,202 --> 00:44:44,986
that Missy went to
Henderson High School.

680
00:44:45,030 --> 00:44:46,596
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS]

681
00:44:46,640 --> 00:44:50,296
She recognized us
from our star high school
football days.

682
00:44:51,340 --> 00:44:53,647
So go figure that.

683
00:44:53,691 --> 00:44:55,475
Kevin Grant suffered
a brain injury,

684
00:44:55,518 --> 00:44:56,955
broken ribs, punctured lung.

685
00:44:56,998 --> 00:45:00,306
He was recovering
in that hospital for a month.

686
00:45:00,349 --> 00:45:03,091
If Danny beat him any more,
he never would've made it.

687
00:45:03,135 --> 00:45:04,789
[DOCTORS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

688
00:45:08,270 --> 00:45:12,100
TONY: Because of the violent
nature of our crime

689
00:45:12,144 --> 00:45:15,669
and the fact that we were
high school football heroes,

690
00:45:15,713 --> 00:45:19,064
our case was front page news
for a few days.

691
00:45:19,107 --> 00:45:21,066
We were advised to take a deal,
so we did.

692
00:45:21,109 --> 00:45:23,198
We agreed to 10 to 25.

693
00:45:26,071 --> 00:45:27,246
[JAIL CELL BUZZER SOUNDS]

694
00:45:27,289 --> 00:45:28,987
[CELL GATE CLOSING]

695
00:45:29,857 --> 00:45:33,165
[INMATES TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

696
00:45:33,208 --> 00:45:36,037
TONY: We were thrown
in St. Charles Parish
Correctional Facility.

697
00:45:36,081 --> 00:45:39,040
Danny was put in a cell
on the opposite side
of the prison from me

698
00:45:39,084 --> 00:45:44,089
and the only contact we had
was the writing of a letter,
or an occasional phone call.

699
00:45:44,132 --> 00:45:45,612
[DOOR BUZZING]

700
00:45:51,487 --> 00:45:52,793
GUARD: All right, let's go.

701
00:45:56,754 --> 00:45:59,104
TONY: I realized during
my time there that

702
00:45:59,147 --> 00:46:03,804
that was an opportunity for me
to change direction in my life,
to make something of myself.

703
00:46:04,849 --> 00:46:06,764
And at that moment,

704
00:46:06,807 --> 00:46:09,854
I felt this overwhelming
sense of gratitude
for my whole situation.

705
00:46:09,897 --> 00:46:13,640
I accepted the fact
that it was a good thing
that we got caught.

706
00:46:15,207 --> 00:46:17,600
I felt sorry for Danny.
I felt responsible for him.

707
00:46:18,645 --> 00:46:20,516
There was nothing I could do.

708
00:46:20,560 --> 00:46:22,127
I wrote him letters

709
00:46:22,170 --> 00:46:25,826
and I tried to get him to admit
that what he did was wrong,

710
00:46:25,870 --> 00:46:30,744
that he was damn lucky
that he did not kill
Kevin Grant that night.

711
00:46:30,788 --> 00:46:33,660
That he had a chance
to do the right thing
from that moment forward.

712
00:46:36,228 --> 00:46:38,056
He didn't listen to me.

713
00:46:38,099 --> 00:46:40,232
He said that he was
just gonna play nice,

714
00:46:40,275 --> 00:46:41,624
he was gonna work the system

715
00:46:41,668 --> 00:46:43,626
because that afforded him
certain privileges

716
00:46:43,670 --> 00:46:47,065
that made life on the inside
a lot easier.

717
00:46:47,108 --> 00:46:48,501
But he just wanted out...

718
00:46:49,632 --> 00:46:50,808
and to stay out.

719
00:46:54,420 --> 00:46:55,508
You two knew them best.

720
00:46:57,553 --> 00:46:59,991
Yeah, Carolyn,
you and Rachel
were like sisters.

721
00:47:00,034 --> 00:47:02,167
I've heard the stories.

722
00:47:02,210 --> 00:47:05,692
And, Mitch, when you say Tony
became a better man
due to his past, I believe it.

723
00:47:05,735 --> 00:47:06,867
I do, Tony.

724
00:47:09,565 --> 00:47:12,481
So Danny's hiding this darkness
inside, I get it, but...

725
00:47:14,092 --> 00:47:15,093
Don't we all?

726
00:47:15,789 --> 00:47:17,878
I mean, it doesn't...

727
00:47:17,922 --> 00:47:20,446
doesn't mean we're all capable
of murdering our families.

728
00:47:20,489 --> 00:47:22,013
BEN: I suppose.

729
00:47:22,056 --> 00:47:25,016
But a crime scene tells a story,
much like Tony's.

730
00:47:25,059 --> 00:47:26,974
And it's up to my guys
to read it correctly.

731
00:47:29,629 --> 00:47:32,980
TONY: Carolyn,
your father, Joe,
his regular visits,

732
00:47:33,024 --> 00:47:36,854
they made all the
difference in the world.
They really did.

733
00:47:36,897 --> 00:47:40,858
Imagine your high school coach
visiting you in jail...

734
00:47:44,731 --> 00:47:46,037
just to remind you that...

735
00:47:48,213 --> 00:47:50,258
the outside world
still cared about you.

736
00:47:53,609 --> 00:47:57,744
And he reminded us
not to give up hope
and to stay strong

737
00:47:57,787 --> 00:47:59,920
because a miracle
could come at any time.

738
00:48:05,447 --> 00:48:06,448
And it did.

739
00:48:10,148 --> 00:48:11,932
In the form of a letter
from Kevin Grant.

740
00:48:13,847 --> 00:48:16,415
He wrote in his letter
that he had come
to the conclusion

741
00:48:16,458 --> 00:48:19,897
that in order to be free,
he needed to forgive.

742
00:48:21,159 --> 00:48:23,509
So he wanted to meet
Danny and me in prison

743
00:48:23,552 --> 00:48:25,554
so he could
forgive us in person.

744
00:48:28,253 --> 00:48:32,039
KEVIN: Yet forgiveness
is an easier thing
to talk about...

745
00:48:32,083 --> 00:48:33,519
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

746
00:48:38,132 --> 00:48:39,220
How are you?

747
00:48:40,874 --> 00:48:43,442
-Orange. Nice.
-[BOTH CHUCKLE]

748
00:48:43,485 --> 00:48:44,747
TONY: Imagine that.

749
00:48:44,791 --> 00:48:46,793
The guy that you had
beat the crap out of

750
00:48:46,836 --> 00:48:50,014
is asking for permission
to forgive you.

751
00:48:50,057 --> 00:48:52,538
[VOICE SHAKING] The honesty
in his letter was undeniable.

752
00:49:03,810 --> 00:49:04,854
Um...

753
00:49:06,552 --> 00:49:08,032
We never properly met.

754
00:49:09,424 --> 00:49:13,080
I was in the hospital
during your trial.

755
00:49:13,124 --> 00:49:16,997
Yeah, last time
we were in the same room
was on that night.

756
00:49:20,653 --> 00:49:22,481
I like the mustache.

757
00:49:22,524 --> 00:49:25,397
I'm so used to seeing you
from the news clippings
of the case.

758
00:49:26,137 --> 00:49:27,616
It makes you look older.

759
00:49:30,271 --> 00:49:31,403
I feel older.

760
00:49:41,326 --> 00:49:42,544
[EXHALES] Um...

761
00:49:52,380 --> 00:49:53,555
After that night...

762
00:49:55,557 --> 00:50:00,780
I spent the next few years
driven crazy with anger.

763
00:50:00,823 --> 00:50:05,393
I'd lie in bed at night
just... just wishing
I'd picked up that bat,

764
00:50:05,437 --> 00:50:07,482
and smashed you both
over the heads.

765
00:50:08,570 --> 00:50:11,008
Why did I not defend my wife?

766
00:50:12,879 --> 00:50:14,837
Listen, Kevin,

767
00:50:14,881 --> 00:50:17,275
-I mean, we're sorry. We just...
-I know you are.

768
00:50:17,318 --> 00:50:19,364
Because you got caught.

769
00:50:19,407 --> 00:50:22,628
But it... it could have easily
have gone the other way.

770
00:50:22,671 --> 00:50:24,804
I could have been killed
and Missy, too.

771
00:50:26,240 --> 00:50:27,807
It could have been much worse.

772
00:50:29,287 --> 00:50:32,333
And it took me
a long time to see that.

773
00:50:35,858 --> 00:50:37,164
But, uh...

774
00:50:39,210 --> 00:50:42,778
after I recovered, I, uh...
I went back to work.

775
00:50:44,302 --> 00:50:45,999
We had our... our son...

776
00:50:49,133 --> 00:50:51,178
and I thought
life would get back to normal.

777
00:50:53,311 --> 00:50:54,660
But instead...

778
00:50:57,880 --> 00:50:59,447
instead I... I...

779
00:50:59,491 --> 00:51:01,406
I sank into a deep depression.

780
00:51:04,017 --> 00:51:05,279
Uh...

781
00:51:06,150 --> 00:51:07,368
One night...

782
00:51:07,412 --> 00:51:08,630
[DOOR CLICKS SHUT]

783
00:51:08,674 --> 00:51:12,156
I was closing up the shop
around 8:00.

784
00:51:12,199 --> 00:51:14,506
And I see this guy Harold,

785
00:51:14,549 --> 00:51:18,249
who often slept
on the grate across the street.

786
00:51:18,292 --> 00:51:22,992
And he was talking
with this well-dressed,
soft-spoken woman.

787
00:51:23,036 --> 00:51:25,430
And, I, uh...

788
00:51:25,473 --> 00:51:29,434
I go to walk past
and he calls out.
He says, "Hey, Kevin..."

789
00:51:29,477 --> 00:51:31,479
-Hey, Kevin.
-"...slow down, man."

790
00:51:31,523 --> 00:51:33,090
-Come on.
-"This is Joanna."

791
00:51:33,133 --> 00:51:36,223
-Come on.
-"She... She's here for you."

792
00:51:38,095 --> 00:51:39,357
[ECHOING] Hi, Kevin.

793
00:51:41,185 --> 00:51:42,447
And, uh...

794
00:51:45,928 --> 00:51:47,713
[SIGHS WEARILY]

795
00:51:49,671 --> 00:51:51,760
That night,

796
00:51:51,804 --> 00:51:55,938
I had brought with me
a bottle of pills,

797
00:51:55,982 --> 00:52:00,900
and I was going to
sit in my car and die.

798
00:52:03,468 --> 00:52:07,646
I couldn't see
the wonderful things
I had to live for,

799
00:52:07,689 --> 00:52:09,300
like Missy,

800
00:52:09,343 --> 00:52:11,432
and my son
and my parents and my friends.

801
00:52:11,476 --> 00:52:17,656
I was...
I was so full of hate for you,

802
00:52:17,699 --> 00:52:21,921
for myself, for... for...
for not being a man
that night that I...

803
00:52:24,576 --> 00:52:29,885
I couldn't see what
my death would do
to those who loved me.

804
00:52:29,929 --> 00:52:31,104
I...

805
00:52:32,323 --> 00:52:34,238
I couldn't see
how much I had to live for.

806
00:52:35,500 --> 00:52:38,372
And all of a sudden,
Joanna took my hand

807
00:52:38,416 --> 00:52:41,680
and she stared intensely
into my eyes,

808
00:52:41,723 --> 00:52:44,291
like she could
look into my mind.

809
00:52:44,335 --> 00:52:46,511
JOANNA: I came to tell you
something, Kevin.

810
00:52:48,426 --> 00:52:50,428
Let go of your anger.

811
00:52:52,517 --> 00:52:54,562
Go home tonight

812
00:52:54,606 --> 00:52:57,217
and pray for the men
that hurt you

813
00:52:57,261 --> 00:52:58,479
and mean it.

814
00:53:00,264 --> 00:53:04,529
Pray that those men you hate
will be happy.

815
00:53:05,530 --> 00:53:07,096
And one day free.

816
00:53:09,360 --> 00:53:13,059
Pray for God to allow you
to forgive them

817
00:53:14,495 --> 00:53:19,021
because that is the only way
you will ever be free.

818
00:53:23,243 --> 00:53:24,723
One more thing, Kevin.

819
00:53:27,639 --> 00:53:33,340
Your plan for tonight
is a very bad idea.

820
00:53:36,517 --> 00:53:39,346
KEVIN: I went back to my car

821
00:53:39,390 --> 00:53:42,958
and I looked
at the bottle of pills.

822
00:53:43,002 --> 00:53:44,699
But instead of taking them...

823
00:53:49,138 --> 00:53:50,227
I prayed.

824
00:53:51,793 --> 00:53:56,058
I out... I prayed out loud
like she told me to.

825
00:53:56,102 --> 00:53:58,887
I prayed for you both

826
00:53:58,931 --> 00:54:00,672
to have a good life.

827
00:54:00,715 --> 00:54:04,719
I prayed
to be able to forgive you.

828
00:54:04,763 --> 00:54:07,113
I prayed to be able
to forgive myself.

829
00:54:09,246 --> 00:54:11,378
And the most
amazing thing happened.

830
00:54:13,380 --> 00:54:14,599
I felt free.

831
00:54:16,470 --> 00:54:17,906
[SIGHS SOFTLY]

832
00:54:32,660 --> 00:54:33,748
Thank you.

833
00:54:38,100 --> 00:54:40,407
TONY: Danny said that

834
00:54:40,451 --> 00:54:47,153
he had these visions
of a woman with gray hair
and olive-colored skin.

835
00:54:47,196 --> 00:54:50,678
He said she was so real
that when he closed his eyes,

836
00:54:50,722 --> 00:54:53,202
she was standing right there
in the cell in front of him.

837
00:54:56,205 --> 00:54:59,731
We had a hearing
for early release.

838
00:54:59,774 --> 00:55:03,038
The committee
overseeing our cases
read letters of support...

839
00:55:05,432 --> 00:55:06,520
from Linda,

840
00:55:07,391 --> 00:55:08,914
and Missy and Kevin Grant.

841
00:55:12,657 --> 00:55:15,355
And the decision
to release us earlier
was unanimous.

842
00:55:18,184 --> 00:55:19,403
[JAIL CELL BUZZER SOUNDS]

843
00:55:42,904 --> 00:55:44,819
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION
AND LAUGHTER]

844
00:55:53,959 --> 00:55:56,091
[PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

845
00:55:56,135 --> 00:55:58,442
-Come on. Come on.
-What you got? What you got?

846
00:55:58,485 --> 00:56:00,139
Run faster! Get in there!

847
00:56:01,140 --> 00:56:03,011
Back up, back up!

848
00:56:03,055 --> 00:56:04,491
ALL: Yeah!

849
00:56:04,535 --> 00:56:07,407
MAN: That's my boy.
That's my boy.
That's my boy.

850
00:56:10,976 --> 00:56:12,107
See you boys next week.

851
00:56:12,151 --> 00:56:13,587
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

852
00:56:15,546 --> 00:56:17,461
[SIGHS]

853
00:56:17,504 --> 00:56:19,463
TONY: All right. I got
a date with Emily tonight.
What are you guys up to?

854
00:56:19,506 --> 00:56:22,640
Good for you.
Maybe she can kiss
your basketball boo-boos.

855
00:56:22,683 --> 00:56:24,337
[CHUCKLES] That's funny.

856
00:56:24,381 --> 00:56:26,034
-Good night, guys.
-See you, buddy.

857
00:56:26,078 --> 00:56:28,210
Hey, speaking of dates...

858
00:56:28,254 --> 00:56:30,691
-I got someone
I want you to meet.
-Oh, come on, man.

859
00:56:30,735 --> 00:56:33,346
-Come on.
Come for a quick drink.
-Come on.

860
00:56:33,390 --> 00:56:37,045
You'd like that... the band.
It's Steve Manano's band.
You like them, right?

861
00:56:37,089 --> 00:56:38,656
-MITCH: Yeah.
-Quick one.

862
00:56:38,699 --> 00:56:40,484
-Okay.
-You'll like her, too,
don't worry.

863
00:56:40,527 --> 00:56:41,963
-Oh, Jesus.
-[DANNY CHUCKLES]

864
00:56:43,487 --> 00:56:46,054
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

865
00:56:49,797 --> 00:56:51,538
Hey, Mike. What up?

866
00:56:51,582 --> 00:56:54,454
-MITCH: What was her name again?
-Her name's, uh, Carolyn.

867
00:56:54,498 --> 00:56:57,109
She went to Henderson High.
Think you might know her.

868
00:56:57,152 --> 00:56:58,589
Hey!

869
00:56:58,632 --> 00:57:00,460
Whoo!

870
00:57:00,504 --> 00:57:02,375
Oh, shit. Look who's here.

871
00:57:02,419 --> 00:57:04,986
Jimmy! Don't you drink too much.
I don't wanna have to
carry you home.

872
00:57:05,030 --> 00:57:07,815
Come on, now. Hear that.
Hear that in your bones?

873
00:57:07,859 --> 00:57:10,557
You gotta feel that music
in your bones. Come on, man.

874
00:57:13,342 --> 00:57:15,475
-CAROLYN: Danny!
-That's my girl!

875
00:57:15,519 --> 00:57:17,477
Hey. Hey, listen!

876
00:57:17,521 --> 00:57:19,697
There's someone
I want to reintroduce you to.

877
00:57:19,740 --> 00:57:21,394
What do you mean, reintroduce?

878
00:57:21,438 --> 00:57:24,266
Yeah. Reintroduce you
because, a long time ago
after a game,

879
00:57:24,310 --> 00:57:26,312
I wanted to introduce you
to my friend Rachel

880
00:57:26,355 --> 00:57:28,662
but you'd taken off
to a keg party or something.

881
00:57:28,706 --> 00:57:31,360
-Yeah, yeah. That sounds
like me back then. I'm sorry.
-Yeah.

882
00:57:31,404 --> 00:57:34,973
-Hey, this is my buddy Mitch,
the one I was telling you about.
-Hi!

883
00:57:35,016 --> 00:57:36,888
-Mitch, this is Carolyn.
-Nice to meet you.

884
00:57:36,931 --> 00:57:38,759
-What?
-Nice to meet you.

885
00:57:38,803 --> 00:57:41,370
Nice to meet you, too. [LAUGHS]

886
00:57:41,414 --> 00:57:44,069
Mitch is a great guy.
He's an okay basketball player,

887
00:57:44,112 --> 00:57:46,071
but he's the best architect
you'll ever meet.

888
00:57:46,114 --> 00:57:48,160
-Oh!
-He designed one of our shops.

889
00:57:48,203 --> 00:57:51,293
Yeah, he was... he graduated
a couple of years ahead of us
at Henderson.

890
00:57:51,337 --> 00:57:53,252
-Oh, okay.
-Oh, you gotta remember
this face.

891
00:57:53,295 --> 00:57:55,210
Look at this guy.
Tall, dark and handsome.

892
00:57:55,254 --> 00:57:56,734
CAROLYN: Sorry. [CHUCKLES]

893
00:57:56,777 --> 00:57:58,736
-It was nice to meet you.
-Likewise.

894
00:57:58,779 --> 00:58:00,477
Yeah.

895
00:58:00,520 --> 00:58:02,653
It's okay. His tongue swells up
when he gets hit
by the love bug.

896
00:58:02,696 --> 00:58:04,524
-Oh.
-Oh, man.

897
00:58:04,568 --> 00:58:07,832
[CHUCKLES] Oh, my God,
there's my friend Rachel.
Okay, come with me.

898
00:58:07,875 --> 00:58:09,398
Hey, do me a favor... Rachel!

899
00:58:09,442 --> 00:58:12,358
-Do not call her Renee again.
-Okay. Okay.

900
00:58:12,401 --> 00:58:13,533
RACHEL: Hi!

901
00:58:13,577 --> 00:58:15,448
-I'm Danny.
-I'm Rachel.

902
00:58:15,492 --> 00:58:18,582
-Right. I remember.
-Yeah.

903
00:58:18,625 --> 00:58:21,976
DANNY: I'm sorry, yeah.
RACHEL: Hey, I love this song.
You wanna dance?

904
00:58:22,020 --> 00:58:25,240
Do you, um, I don't know,
wanna have a drink?

905
00:58:26,590 --> 00:58:28,766
-Why not?
-Okay.

906
00:58:28,809 --> 00:58:31,159
DANNY: What do you like
for breakfast in the morning?

907
00:58:31,203 --> 00:58:32,987
That's a really bad question
to ask.

908
00:58:33,031 --> 00:58:35,163
-That sounds really terrible.
Forget it.
-[LAUGHS]

909
00:58:35,207 --> 00:58:38,166
-Are you inviting me
to breakfast?
-Yeah, that's why it sounds bad.

910
00:58:38,210 --> 00:58:39,864
I wasn't asking you
that kind of...

911
00:58:39,907 --> 00:58:42,257
Forget I asked you that.
Just dance with me.

912
00:58:42,301 --> 00:58:44,085
Come on.

913
00:58:44,129 --> 00:58:47,132
[MUSIC PLAYING]

914
00:58:53,573 --> 00:58:54,879
Club soda, please.

915
00:59:01,450 --> 00:59:03,540
CAROLYN: How's your drink?
Strong enough for you?

916
00:59:04,758 --> 00:59:07,631
♪ You seein' my baby walking

917
00:59:07,674 --> 00:59:10,198
♪ Tell her I caught my train
And gone

918
00:59:13,201 --> 00:59:15,552
♪ If you see my baby walkin'

919
00:59:16,640 --> 00:59:18,685
[ALARM RINGING]

920
00:59:20,121 --> 00:59:21,122
[ALARM STOPS]

921
00:59:35,789 --> 00:59:37,704
[TV BEEPS]

922
00:59:37,748 --> 00:59:41,752
I'm standing at the edge
of Nicholson Quarry
in St. Francisville

923
00:59:41,795 --> 00:59:46,539
where the final act
of the Turner family tragedy
took place Tuesday morning.

924
00:59:46,583 --> 00:59:49,803
It was here that Danny Turner,

925
00:59:49,847 --> 00:59:53,198
husband and father
of the victims,
took his own life.

926
00:59:53,241 --> 00:59:57,637
Though the final report
has not yet been released
by the medical examiner...

927
00:59:57,681 --> 00:59:59,073
[TV BEEPS OFF]

928
01:00:13,566 --> 01:00:16,090
RACHEL: [VOICEMAIL RECORDING]
Hey, sweetie, it's Rachel.

929
01:00:16,134 --> 01:00:19,441
What are you up to?
I'm about to go take my exam,
and I just was calling...

930
01:00:22,619 --> 01:00:23,924
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

931
01:00:38,460 --> 01:00:39,592
Ben.

932
01:00:41,550 --> 01:00:43,335
Thank you for agreeing
to meet with me.

933
01:00:43,378 --> 01:00:46,381
Glad you reached out.

934
01:00:46,425 --> 01:00:50,255
BEN: Look, I didn't want
to get into all these details
in front of the family.

935
01:00:50,298 --> 01:00:51,996
But, uh...

936
01:00:52,039 --> 01:00:54,172
This is kinda what happened.

937
01:00:54,215 --> 01:00:56,565
Danny told Logan
that he wanted him to help

938
01:00:56,609 --> 01:01:00,918
fake a jewelry heist
at his house to make
an insurance claim of $30,000,

939
01:01:00,961 --> 01:01:03,224
which he said
he would share with Logan.

940
01:01:03,268 --> 01:01:05,444
Logan said he didn't think
it was really a crime.

941
01:01:05,487 --> 01:01:07,968
So they left Logan's car
at R.J. Vale Elementary school

942
01:01:08,012 --> 01:01:09,840
and then drove
to Danny's house together.

943
01:01:09,883 --> 01:01:11,668
Now here's
where it gets interesting.

944
01:01:11,711 --> 01:01:14,758
Around 11:30 p.m.,
Danny came back

945
01:01:14,801 --> 01:01:16,498
and told Logan
that Rachel was asleep

946
01:01:16,542 --> 01:01:18,413
and to break the glass
in the back door
of the garage

947
01:01:18,457 --> 01:01:20,328
to make it look
like a break-in.

948
01:01:20,372 --> 01:01:23,201
[WHISPERS] And I want you
to put a brick through
the window, okay?

949
01:01:23,244 --> 01:01:25,682
You do that for me.
Make it look like we,
you know...

950
01:01:25,725 --> 01:01:27,727
just like somebody
robbed the house, got it?

951
01:01:27,771 --> 01:01:29,381
-All right.
-You got a phone on you.

952
01:01:29,424 --> 01:01:30,991
BEN: Now according
to phone records,

953
01:01:31,035 --> 01:01:33,341
Danny then made several calls
in the next few hours,

954
01:01:33,385 --> 01:01:36,562
including one to his brother
and several to Logan's friends

955
01:01:36,605 --> 01:01:38,825
in which he claimed
that he had just fired Logan

956
01:01:38,869 --> 01:01:41,219
and Logan
had threatened to kill him.

957
01:01:41,262 --> 01:01:43,221
[CLEARS THROAT] Hey, Tony.

958
01:01:43,264 --> 01:01:45,571
It's Danny. Um...

959
01:01:45,614 --> 01:01:47,573
Listen, I... I just fired Logan.

960
01:01:47,616 --> 01:01:49,444
Doesn't this Logan guy
also have a record?

961
01:01:49,488 --> 01:01:51,795
I mean, why do the police
believe what he has to say?

962
01:01:51,838 --> 01:01:55,276
Okay, so, Logan has a record,
but his statements check out.

963
01:01:55,320 --> 01:01:58,149
Look, when you're dealing
with a crime like this,
it's very common

964
01:01:58,192 --> 01:02:00,629
for witnesses to be people
with dicey backgrounds.

965
01:02:00,673 --> 01:02:02,457
We know Logan isn't a Boy Scout.

966
01:02:02,501 --> 01:02:04,111
The fact that Danny
made these calls

967
01:02:04,155 --> 01:02:06,287
suggests that he was trying
to frame Logan

968
01:02:06,331 --> 01:02:08,768
and create an alibi
for himself.

969
01:02:08,812 --> 01:02:11,292
You think it was premeditated?

970
01:02:11,336 --> 01:02:13,555
BEN: Around 1:00 a.m.,
he came back

971
01:02:13,599 --> 01:02:16,733
and said that he never
really planned to steal
any jewelry.

972
01:02:16,776 --> 01:02:18,778
In fact, there wasn't
any jewelry to steal.

973
01:02:18,822 --> 01:02:22,129
-Instead, he wanted
Logan's help killing Rachel.
-There's a change of plan.

974
01:02:22,173 --> 01:02:24,871
I, uh... I need to...
I need to kill my wife.

975
01:02:24,915 --> 01:02:27,831
Okay? So I need you to do it
